stories: Bias triangles are a feature of stability diagrams in quantum dot (QD) devices, and their analysis is crucial for understanding spin physics. However, challenges associated with data quality and availability, as well as the subtlety of the physical phenomena of interest, have hindered the development of an automatic and bespoke analysis framework. This framework often relies on human labelling and verification. To address this, we introduce a feature extraction framework for bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification of physical properties of the former. This approach circumvents the need for human input or large training datasets to inform supervised learning approaches, while also enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and feature labeling. We demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (PSB) detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently, and without any training data as a result of this approach.
